<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,437,570]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,473,498]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Notes.</emphasis>
Specialist on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hicks" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[430,553,473,498]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Helianthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[430,553,473,498]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Helianthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[567,697,473,497]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
). Nest from 
<collectingRegion box="[834,915,474,497]" country="United States of America" name="Kansas" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Kansas</collectingRegion>
described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Danforth" box="[1070,1255,473,498]" firstAuthor="Danforth" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="59 - 79" refId="ref86534" refString="Danforth, B. N. (1989) Nesting behavior of four species of Perdita (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 62, 59 - 79." type="journal article" year="1989">Danforth (1989)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wolf &amp; Ascher" firstAuthor="Wolf" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="129 - 168" refId="ref106106" refString="Wolf, A. T. &amp; Ascher, J. S. (2009) Bees of Wisconsin (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Anthophila). The Great Lakes Entomologist, 41, 129 - 168." type="journal article" year="2009">Wolf &amp; Ascher (2009)</bibRefCitation>
expressed doubt regarding the status of this subspecies, and suggested it may be a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="Viereck" authorityName="Viereck" authorityYear="1917" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaerti">
<emphasis box="[1301,1436,509,534]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">P. bequaerti</emphasis>
Viereck
</taxonomicName>
(see below). If correct, then only a single species of 
<taxonomicName box="[829,912,545,570]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[829,912,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Perdita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Ashmead, 1898" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1898" box="[929,1059,545,570]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Cockerellia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[929,1059,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Cockerellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) would be present in 
<collectingRegion box="[1301,1412,545,570]" country="United States of America" name="Michigan" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Michigan</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
